\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Probability and Statistics - P&P 5 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Submission by: Elia Yakin & Itay Koren
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Suppose that you received a free subscription to the lottery and you want
 to know whether you are in the regular track (probability 0.1 to win) or
 the premium track (probability 0.25 to win).
 To this end, you start counting the weeks in which you participated up
 to (and including) the first win.
 You set a decision rule: If you win before week 6, you will conclude that
 you are on the premium track.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(1) Define an appropriate random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and determine its distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(2) Formulate the hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(3) Write the rejection region of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 it terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(4) Compute type I and type II errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Answer: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) From the above we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 being a series of random bernouli trials 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\sim Ber\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 up to the on in which win the lottery.
 this description fits the geometric distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim Geo\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is dependant on the track 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\begin{cases}
0.1 & regular\ track\\
0.25 & premium\ track
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:\ \theta=0.1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}:\ \theta=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 we reject 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 if we win before week 6, i.e.
 the rejection region is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Omega_{1} & =\left\{ k\,:\ k<6\right\} \\
\Omega_{0} & =\left\{ k\,:\ k\geq6\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P\left(X<6\right) & =1-\left(1-\theta\right)^{5}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha & =P_{\theta_{0}}\left(X<6\right)=1-\left(1-\theta_{0}\right)^{5}=1-0.9^{5}=0.40951\\
\beta & =P_{\theta_{1}}\left(X\geq6\right)=\left(1-\theta_{1}\right)^{5}=0.75^{5}=0.2373
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
The advertisement of the fast food chain of restaurants “FastBurger” claims
 that the average waiting time for food in its branches is 30 seconds unlike
 the 50 seconds of their competitors.
 Mr.
 Skeptic does not believe much in advertising and decided to test its truth
 by the following test: he will go to one of the “FastBurger” branches,
 measure the waiting time, and if it is less than 40 seconds (the critical
 waiting time he fixed) he would believe in its advertisement.
 Otherwise, he will conclude that the service in “FastBurger” is no faster
 than in other fast food companies.
 Mr.Skeptic also assumes that waiting time is exponentially distributed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(1) What are the hypotheses Mr.
 Skeptic tests? Calculate the probabilities of errors of both types for
 his test.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(2) Can you suggest a better test to Mr.
 Skeptic with the same significance level?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H_{0} & :\theta=50\\
H_{1} & :\theta=30
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha & =P_{H_{0}}\left(\overline{X}<40\right)=1-e^{-\theta_{0}\cdot40}=1-e^{-0.0005}\approx0.02\\
\beta & =P_{H_{1}}\left(\overline{X}\geq40\right)=1-\left(1-e^{-\theta_{1}\cdot0.4}\right)=e^{-0.3\cdot0.4}=e^{-0.012}\approx0.98\\
\alpha & =P_{H_{0}}\left(\overline{X}<40\right)=\Phi\left(\frac{40-30}{1/30/1}\right)=\Phi\left(300\right)\\
\alpha & =P_{H_{0}}\left(\overline{X}\geq40\right)=1-\Phi\left(\frac{40-50}{1/50/1}\right)=1-\Phi\left(-500\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 (2) we can use Neyman-Pearson's lemma to ensure higher power given the
 same 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(x\right) & =\frac{L\left(30,x_{i}\right)}{L\left(50,x_{i}\right)}=\frac{P_{H_{1}}\left(x_{i}\right)}{P_{H_{0}}\left(x_{i}\right)}=\frac{1-e^{-0.3x_{i}}}{1-e^{-0.5x_{i}}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 be i.i.d s.t 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}'s$
\end_inset

 pdf is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{\theta}\left(x\right) & =\frac{x}{\theta}\cdot e^{-\frac{x^{2}}{2\theta}}\ \ x\geq0,\theta>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Use the Neyman-Pearson lemma to find the most powerful test at level 
\begin_inset Formula $α$
\end_inset

 for testing the two simple hypotheses: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H_{0}: & \theta=\theta_{0}\\
H_{1}: & \theta=\theta_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}>\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 hint 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{2}/\theta\sim\chi_{2n}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we want to find a simplification 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 s.t 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(T\left(x\right)>c\right)$
\end_inset

 for the rejection region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(x\right) & =\frac{\mathcal{L}\left(\theta_{1},X\right)}{\mathcal{L}\left(\theta_{0},X\right)}=\frac{P\left(X=X_{1},X=X_{2},\dots,X=X_{n};\theta_{1}\right)}{P\left(X=X_{1},X=X_{2},\dots,X=X_{n};\theta_{0}\right)}\\
 & \underset{iid}{=}\frac{\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}}{\theta_{1}}\cdot e^{-\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{2\theta_{1}}}}{\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}}{\theta_{0}}\cdot e^{-\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{2\theta_{0}}}}=\frac{\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{1}}\right)^{n}\cdot\prod_{i=1}^{n}e^{-\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{2\theta_{1}}}}{\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{0}}\right)^{n}\cdot\prod_{i=1}^{n}e^{-\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{2\theta_{0}}}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)^{n}\cdot\frac{e^{-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{\theta_{1}}}}{e^{-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{\theta_{0}}}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{\theta_{1}}-\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{\theta_{0}}\right)}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{1}}-\frac{1}{\theta_{0}}\right)\right)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}>\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and that the rejection region is so by mnipulation we can do the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\{ \lambda\left(X\right)\geq c\right\}  & =\left\{ \left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{1}}-\frac{1}{\theta_{0}}\right)\right)}\geq c\right\} \\
 & =\left\{ n\cdot log\left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{1}}-\frac{1}{\theta_{0}}\right)\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\geq log\left(c\right)\right\} \\
 & \underset{\theta_{1}>\theta_{0}}{=}\left\{ \sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\geq\frac{log\left(c\right)-n\cdot log\left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)}{\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{0}}-\frac{1}{\theta_{1}}\right)}\right\} \\
 & c^{*}:=\frac{log\left(c\right)-n\cdot log\left(\frac{\theta_{0}}{\theta_{1}}\right)}{\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{\theta_{0}}-\frac{1}{\theta_{1}}\right)}\\
 & \implies\left\{ \sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{2}\geq c^{*}\right\} \underset{\theta_{0}>0}{\iff}\left\{ \sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{2}/\theta_{0}\geq c^{*}/\theta_{0}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 and because 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}/\theta\sim\chi_{2n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha & =P_{H_{0}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{2}/\theta_{0}\geq c^{*}/\theta_{0}\right)=1-P_{H_{0}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}^{2}/\theta_{0}\leq c^{*}/\theta_{0}\right)\iff c^{*}=\theta_{0}\chi_{2n,1-\alpha}^{2}\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
The lifetime of an automatic gear has normal distribution with known standard
 deviation of 30,000 km.
 The manufacturer claims that the expected lifetime is more than 120,000
 km.
 To test the claim of the manufacturer, a sample of 15 cars was drawn.
 The average lifetime of the cars in the sample is 135,320 km.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(1) Formulate the hypotheses 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(2) Would you reject the null hypothesis with significance level of 5%?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(3) What is the minimal significance level for which you would reject the
 null?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H_{0}: & \mu\leq120,000\\
H_{1}: & \mu>120,000
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 (2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
PV & =\underset{\mu\in M_{0}}{sup}P_{\mu,H_{0}}\left(T\left(x\right)\leq t_{obs}\right)\\
 & =P_{\mu_{0}}\left(\overline{X}\leq135,320\right)\\
 & \iff\\
PV & =\phi\left(\frac{135,320-120,000}{30,000/\sqrt{15}}\right)=\phi\left(\sqrt{15}\frac{383}{750}\right)=\phi\left(1.977\right)=0.024
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 we clearly reject the null in 0.05 significance level as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.05>0.024$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) the minimal significance level we choose is the p-value which is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.024$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
In the lecture, we saw that for 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},...,X_{n}\overset{i.i.d.}{\sim}N\left(\theta,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $σ^{2}$
\end_inset

 known), the two-sided hypothesis test for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H_{0} & \theta=\theta_{0}\\
H_{1} & \theta\neq\theta_{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 is given by the rejection region 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R & \left\{ \left|\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}\right|\geq c\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Show that for significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $α$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=z_{1−α/2}\cdot\sigma/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha & =P_{H_{o}}\left(\left|\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}\right|\geq c\right)\\
 & =P_{H_{o}}\left(\left\{ c\leq\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}\right\} \cup\left\{ \overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}\leq-c\right\} \right)\\
 & =P_{H_{o}}\left(c\leq\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}\right)+P_{H_{o}}\left(\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}\leq-c\right)\\
 & =P_{H_{o}}\left(\frac{c+\theta_{0}-\theta_{0}}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\leq\frac{\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)+P_{H_{o}}\left(\frac{\overline{X}_{n}-\theta_{0}}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\leq\frac{-c}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)\\
 & =1-\Phi\left(\frac{c}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)+\Phi\left(\frac{-c}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)\\
 & \underset{\Phi\ symmetric}{=}2\cdot\left(1-\Phi\left(\frac{c}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)\right)\\
 & \iff\\
 & \Phi^{-1}\left(1-\alpha/2\right)=z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}=\frac{c}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\iff c=z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\cdot\sigma/\sqrt{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
This problem is a guided proof of the well-known one-sample t-test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},...,X_{n}\overset{i.i.d.}{\sim}N\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $σ^{2}$
\end_inset

 is unknown, and we want to test 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:\mu=\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

 against the two-sided alternative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\neq\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote for simplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(1) Write the likelihood function of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},..,X_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(2) Plug-in the MLE estimators for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $σ^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the likelihood function.
 Explain why the obtained expression is 
\begin_inset Formula $sup_{\theta\in\Theta}\mathcal{L}\left(\theta;X\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
(3) Plug-in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{σ}^{2}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the likelihood function.
 Explain why the obtained expression is 
\begin_inset Formula $sup_{\theta\in\Theta_{0}}\mathcal{L}\left(\theta;X\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) Show that the generalized likelihood ratio is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda^{*}\left(X\right) & =\left(1+\frac{1}{n+1}\left(\frac{\overline{X_{n}}-\mu_{0}}{s/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}\right)^{n/2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(5) Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T\left(X\right) & =\frac{\overline{X_{n}}-\mu_{0}}{s/\sqrt{n}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explain why the rejection region 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \lambda^{*}\left(X\right)\geq c\right\} $
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the rejection region 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ T\left(X\right)\geq c^{*}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(6) What is the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(7) Find the critical 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}\left(\theta;X\right) & =P\left(\bigcap_{i=1}^{n}X=X_{i}\right)\underset{iid}{=}\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 (2) Reminder: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\theta_{MLE} & =\left(\mu_{MLE},\sigma_{MLE}^{2}\right)=\left(\overline{X}_{n},\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}\left(\theta_{MLE};X\right) & =\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}}{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}\right)}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\sum_{n=1}^{n}x_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}}{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}_{n}\right)}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\left(\hat{\sigma}_{MLE}^{2}2\pi\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}}e^{-\frac{n}{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 we know that we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{MLE}$
\end_inset

 by taking the FOC of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\cdot,X\right)$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{MLE}=argmax_{\theta\in\Theta}\mathcal{L}\left(\theta,X\right)$
\end_inset

 and under the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $sup\left\{ \Theta\right\} \subseteq\Theta$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{MLE}=sup\left\{ \Theta\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) under the null space 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}=\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\hat{\mu}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 thus we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}\left(\left(\mu_{0},\hat{σ}^{2}\right);X\right) & =\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x_{i}-\mu_{0}}{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\sigma_{0}^{2}2\pi\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}}e^{-\frac{n}{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) we need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda^{*}\left(X\right) & =\left(1+\frac{1}{n+1}\left(\frac{\overline{X_{n}}-\mu_{0}}{s/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}\right)^{n/2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to do so we can use the previous results, but before that for an unknown
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

we can write 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(X\right) & =\frac{sup_{\theta\in\Theta}\mathcal{L}\left(\theta,X\right)}{sup_{\theta\in\Theta_{0}}\mathcal{L}\left(\theta,X\right)}=\frac{\mathcal{L}\left(\theta_{MLE},X\right)}{\mathcal{L}\left(\theta_{0},X\right)}\\
 & =\frac{\left(\hat{\sigma}_{MLE}^{2}2\pi\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}}e^{-\frac{n}{2}}}{\left(\sigma_{0}^{2}2\pi\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}}e^{-\frac{n}{2}}}=\frac{\left(\hat{\sigma}_{MLE}^{2}\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}}}{\left(\sigma_{0}^{2}\right)^{-\frac{n}{2}}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sigma_{0}^{2}}{\hat{\sigma}_{MLE}^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}+\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)+\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)\right)^{2}}{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}+\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}+2\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)}{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}+n\cdot\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}+2\cdot0\cdot\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)}{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}+n\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{n\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\left(\frac{n-1}{n-1}\right)\frac{1}{n}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\left(\frac{n-1}{n}\right)\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{n=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{\left(\frac{n-1}{n}\right)s^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\left(\frac{n}{n-1}\right)\frac{\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{0}\right)^{2}}{s^{2}}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\frac{\overline{X}-\mu_{0}}{s/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 (5) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(X\right)=\frac{\overline{X_{n}}-\mu_{0}}{s/\sqrt{n}}$
\end_inset

 thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(x\right) & =\left(1+\frac{1}{n-1}T\left(X\right)^{2}\right)^{\frac{n}{2}}\ge c\\
\underset{}{\iff} & 1+\frac{1}{n-1}T\left(X\right)^{2}\ge c^{\frac{2}{n}}\\
\underset{n>1}{\iff} & T\left(X\right)^{2}\geq\left(n-1\right)\left(c^{\frac{2}{n}}-1\right)\\
\underset{*}{\iff} & \left|T\left(X\right)\right|\geq\left(\left(n-1\right)\left(c^{\frac{2}{n}}-1\right)\right)^{1/2}:=c^{*}\\
\iff & \left|T\left(X\right)\right|\geq c^{*}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 *: T
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

could be negative or positive, thus we need to take it's absolute value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(6) 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 distribution is the known Student's t-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom (why is it only one df less? whe have 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 we estimate out of the sample)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(7) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha & =sup_{\theta\in\Theta_{0}}P_{\theta}\left(\left|T\left(x\right)\right|\geq c^{*}\right)=P_{\theta_{0}}\left(\left|T\left(x\right)\right|\geq c^{*}\right)\\
 & \underset{t\ symetric}{=}2P_{\theta_{0}}\left(T\left(x\right)\geq c^{*}\right)=2\left(1-P_{\theta_{0}}\left(T\left(x\right)\leq c^{*}\right)\right)\\
 & \iff\\
c & ^{*}=t_{n-1,1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

